// Add these entries to your VSCode User settings.json on the LOCAL machine
// (not the remote VM). They free Ctrl-G and Ctrl-O in the terminal so
// dux's exit_interactive keybind and Claude Code's Ctrl-O (toggle verbose
// / multi-line) reach the running PTY instead of being captured by VS Code.
//
// Background: VS Code's "commandsToSkipShell" controls which Workbench
// commands flow through to the integrated terminal. By default it
// intercepts a curated allowlist — including the bindings for Goto Line,
// Recent Directory, and Open File — which means key combinations bound
// to those commands never reach the program running in the terminal,
// even when that program (dux, claude, etc.) wants to handle them itself.
// The "-" prefix on each entry tells VS Code to STOP intercepting that
// command, falling back to the default of forwarding it to the shell.
//
// Reload the VS Code window (Cmd/Ctrl-Shift-P → "Reload Window") after
// editing for the change to take effect on existing terminals.
{
  "terminal.integrated.commandsToSkipShell": [
    "-workbench.action.gotoLine",
    "-workbench.action.terminal.goToRecentDirectory",
    "-workbench.action.files.openFile"
  ]
}
